1 SECTION 5. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 34.5.2A of Title 62, unless
3 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 A. The Governor shall appoint, with the advice and consent of
5 the Senate, a Chief Operating Officer (COO) of the State of
6 Oklahoma.
7 B. The COO shall have a four-year degree in public
8 administration, business management or a related field, and not less
9 than eight (8) years' experience, with progressive responsibility
10 and management, in public budget administration, or in a related
11 position involving administrative or operational responsibility, or
12 any equivalent combination of experience and training.
13 C. The COO shall be selected with special reference to his or
14 her training, experience, capacity and interest in the activities
15 embraced within Title 74 of the Oklahoma Statutes and other
16 applicable provisions of law. The COO's knowledge, experience, and
17 demonstrated abilities should encompass each of the following:
18 1. A comprehensive knowledge of the principles and practices of
19 public administration and organizational management, and a working
20 knowledge of governmental accounting;
21 2. An extensive knowledge of the organization and operations of
22 state departments, agencies and institutions, and of principles of
23 public organization and administration;
24
